    <h1>XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) Explained</h1>
    <p>XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) is a type of cyber attack in which malicious scripts are injected into legitimate websites or web applications. These scripts can be used to steal sensitive information, deface websites, or redirect users to malicious websites.</p>
    <p>XSS attacks can occur in several ways, including:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Reflected XSS:</strong> The attacker injects malicious scripts into a URL parameter, which is then reflected back to the user by the web application. This can happen when the application does not properly validate or sanitize user input.</li>
        <li><strong>Stored XSS:</strong> The attacker injects malicious scripts into a database or other persistent storage, which is then displayed to users by the web application. This can happen when the application does not properly validate or sanitize user input.</li>
        <li><strong>Dom-based XSS:</strong> The attacker exploits vulnerabilities in the web application's JavaScript code to inject malicious scripts into the DOM (Document Object Model). This can happen when the application does not properly validate or sanitize user input.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>To prevent XSS attacks, web applications should use the following best practices:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Input Validation:</strong> Validate user input to ensure that it contains only allowed characters and formats. Use regular expressions or other techniques to validate input.</li>
        <li><strong>Output Encoding:</strong> Use HTML encoding to prevent special characters from being interpreted as HTML tags. Use the <code>&lt;%@ page encodeURI="true"%&gt;</code> directive in Java or the <code>htmlentities()</code> function in PHP to encode output.</li>
        <li><strong>Content Security Policy (CSP):</strong> Use CSP to restrict the sources of scripts and other content that can be loaded by the web application. This can prevent XSS attacks by blocking malicious scripts from being injected into the web application.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>By following these best practices, web applications can significantly reduce the risk of XSS attacks.</p>
